Chapter 03

date: 2017-08-17 moderator: Jonas

Chapter 3 summary

  • Counting: The best thing about Bayesian, you don’t can simply think empirically by counting things. Everything is counts, even probability distributions. By using this “empirical attack” on the posterior, a difficult problem of integral calculus is transformed into an easy problem of summarising samples.

  • Bayesian about Hypothesis testing: The question in Hypothsis testing is, whether the signal from out model about the Hypothesis is real. The biggest impact on this question is not how well you test, but how realistic you choose your hypothesis. Statistical learning is not about fancy testing, but about thinking.

  • Describe the Posterior: The highest posterior density interval is the slimmest interval that holds a given fraction of the posterior samples. It is not often reported but it does make a lot of sense. In the end, you need to ask you, what is the easiest way to report your posterior. If it is a weird skewed one, just give the whole distribution.

  • Point estimates: As a researcher you normall want to report a good picture of the posterior, and here point estimates are not helpful. But for decision making, point estimates make sense. In this case, the estimate of choice will depend on the loss-function. So what is the penalty/cost for the estimate being to high or too small.

Chapter 3 - Exercises

p_grid <- seq( from=0 , to=1 , length.out=1000 ) 
prior <- rep( 1 , 1000 ) 
likelihood <- dbinom( 6 , size=9 , prob=p_grid ) 
posterior <- likelihood * prior 
posterior <- posterior / sum(posterior) 
set.seed(100) 
samples <- sample( p_grid , prob=posterior , size=1e4 , replace=TRUE )
# 3E1. How much posterior probability lies below p = 0.2?
library(tidyverse)
library(rethinking)
dens( samples ) # visual inspection
abline( v=6/9 )

mean( samples<0.2 ) # 0.0005, so very unlikely
[1] 5e-04
# 3E2. How much posterior probability lies above p = 0.8?
mean( samples>0.8 ) # 0.1117, so much more
[1] 0.1117
# 3E3. How much posterior probability lies between p = 0.2 and p = 0.8?
mean( samples>0.2 & samples<0.8 ) # 0.8878
[1] 0.8878

samples %>% quantile( 0.2 ) # 0.5195195
      20% 
0.5195195 
# 3E5. 20% of the posterior probability lies above which value of p?
samples %>% quantile( 1-0.2 ) # 0.7568
      80% 
0.7567568

## Medium.
# 3M1. Suppose the globe tossing data had turned out to be 8 water in 15 tosses. Construct the posterior distribution, using grid approximation. Use the same flat prior as before.
p_grid <- seq( from=0 , to=1 , length.out=1000 )
prior <- rep( 1, length( p_grid ) )
likelihood <- dbinom( x=8 , size=15 , prob=p_grid )
posterior <- prior * likelihood
posterior <- posterior / sum( posterior )
plot( p_grid , posterior , type ='l' )

# 3M2. Draw 10,000 samples from the grid approximation from above. Then use the samples to calculate the 90% HPDI for p.
samples <- sample( p_grid , prob=posterior , size=1e4 , replace=T )
dens( samples )

HPDI( samples , prob=.90 )
     |0.9      0.9| 
0.3323323 0.7267267 
# 3M3. Construct a posterior predictive check for this model and data. This means simulate the distribution of samples, averaging over the posterior uncertainty in p. What is the probability of observing 8 water in 15 tosses?
ppc <- rbinom( n=length(samples) , size=15 , prob=samples )  
simplehist( ppc )

mean( ppc == 8 ) # it is 0.1397
[1] 0.1427
# 3M4. Using the posterior distribution constructed from the new (8/15) data, now calculate the probability of observing 6 water in 9 tosses.
# I guess this means using the posterior now as a prior
prior2 <- posterior
likelihood <- dbinom( x=6 , size=9 , prob=p_grid )
posterior2 <- prior2 * likelihood
posterior2 <- posterior2 / sum( posterior2 )
plot( p_grid , posterior2 , type='l' )

# 3M5. Start over at 3M1, but now use a prior that is zero below p = 0.5 and a constant above p = 0.5. This corresponds to prior information that a majority of the Earth’s surface is water. Repeat each problem above and compare the inferences. What difference does the better prior make? If it helps, compare inferences (using both priors) to the true value p = 0.7.
priorM5 <- ifelse( p_grid<0.5 , 0 , 1 )
#
likelihood <- dbinom( x=8 , size=15 , prob=p_grid )
# old
posterior <- prior * likelihood
posterior <- posterior / sum( posterior )
plot( p_grid , posterior , type ='l' )

# new
posterior_n <- priorM5 * likelihood
posterior_n <- posterior_n / sum( posterior_n )
plot( p_grid , posterior_n , type ='l' )

# where there is nothing in the prior, there is nothing in the posterior

# 3H1. Using grid approximation, compute the posterior distribution for the probability of a birth being a boy. Assume a uniform prior probability. 
p_vec <- seq( from=0 , to=1 , length.out=1000 ) # parameter p and its conjectures
prior <- rep( 1 , length( p_vec ) ) # boy , girl, [counts of these 2 conjectures to happen, without data]
## turn data into observation
all_births <- c( birth1 , birth2 )
nboys <- sum( all_births ) # 111
size <- length( all_births ) # 200
##
likelihood <- dbinom( x=nboys , size=size , prob=p_vec )
# update prior
posterior <- prior * likelihood
posterior <- posterior / sum( posterior )
plot( p_vec , posterior , type='l' )

# Which parameter value maximizes the posterior probability?
p_vec[ which.max(posterior) ] # 0.554
[1] 0.5545546
# 3H2. Using the sample function, draw 10,000 random parameter values from the posterior distribution you calculated above. Use these samples to estimate the 50%, 89%, and 97% highest posterior density intervals.
samples <- sample( p_vec , prob=posterior , size=1e4 , replace=T )
samples %>% HPDI(0.5)
     |0.5      0.5|

# 3H3. Use rbinom to simulate 10,000 replicates of 200 births. You should end up with 10,000 numbers, each one a count of boys out of 200 births. Compare the distribution of predicted numbers of boys to the actual count in the data (111 boys out of 200 births). There are many good ways to visualize the simulations, but the dens command (part of the rethinking package) is probably the easiest way in this case. Does it look like the model fits the data well? That is, does the distribution of predictions include the actual observation as a central, likely outcome?
fp_sims <- rbinom( n=1e4 , size=200 , prob=samples )
fp_sims %>% length()
[1] 10000
dens( fp_sims ); abline( v=111 ) # it looks like a good fit indeed

# 3H5. The model assumes that sex of first and second births are independent. To check this assumption, focus now on second births that followed female first borns. Compare 10,000 simulated counts of boys to only those second births that followed girls. To do this correctly, you need to count the number of first borns who were girls and simulate that many births, 10,000 times. Compare the counts of boys in your simulations to the actual observed count of boys following girls. How does the model look in this light? Any guesses what is going on in these data?
b2_aftergirl <- birth2[birth1 == 0]
size <- length( b2_aftergirl ) # 49
nboys <- sum( b2_aftergirl ) # 39
likelihood <- dbinom( x=nboys , size=size , prob=p_vec )
posterior <- prior * likelihood
posterior <- posterior / sum( posterior )
plot( p_vec , posterior , type='l' )

# posterior sample and future prodiction simulation
samples <- sample( p_vec , prob=posterior , size=1e4 , replace=T )
fp_sims <- rbinom( n=1e4 , size=size , prob=samples )
dens( fp_sims/size , adj=0.9); abline( v=39/size ,col='red') # it still looks good
